				<div class="lockerroom-entry">
					<div class="lockerrooom-entry-title">
						Football <span class="by">by</span> Sage Rosenfels
						<div class="author-image" style="background-image: url(https://s3.amazonaws.com/footballbyfootball-dev/Headshots/pro_sagerosenfels.jpg)"></div>
					</div>
					<div class="lockerrooom-entry-content">
						<p>My favorite season opening game came in 2010 as a member of the New York Giants. I had been traded from the Vikings just eight days prior after Brett Favre came back for a second year with that team. I was swimming mentally, as I spent every waking second that week trying to learn Kevin Gilbride’s offense. 

						<p>The reason that game is so special to me is because it was the regular season opening of Met-Life Stadium. Coach Tom Coughlin mentioned the importance of the game, knowing that the score would be noted in the team program for decades to come. We beat the Carolina Panthers in the spectacular $1.6 Billion stadium.  But the best part for me came after the game. 

						<p>Sitting next to Eli Manning in the locker room as the media started to flow in, I saw him take off his jersey and stuff it into his personal bag. I’d never taken a jersey after a game before, so I was hesitant to copy him. I asked Eli “Is it OK if we take our jerseys?” He responded “I’m taking this one.” 

						<p>I still have that jersey sitting in my closet. It has a patch on the shoulder commemorating the game. Not a word was said to me in the following days as to the whereabouts of my jersey. Believe it or not, most teams would have charged me for it.  That was my first taste of why so many people say the Giants are one of the classiest teams to play for in the NFL. 
					</div>
