			<div class="row">
				<div class="lockerroom-entry">
					<div class="lockerrooom-entry-title">
						Football <span class="by">by</span> Matt Chatham
						<div class="author-image" style="background-image: url(https://s3.amazonaws.com/footballbyfootball-dev/Headshots/pro_mattchatham.jpg)"></div>
					</div>

					<div class="lockerrooom-entry-content">
						<img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/footballbyfootball-dev/lockerroom/lock-ozzysigned.jpg" alt="" style="float: left; padding: 20px; padding-left: 0;">

						<p>The 2005 Thursday NFL Kickoff game had all the energy, pomp and circumstance that you’d expect from an NFL opener. But that one was different. 
						 
						<p>It wasn’t just banner night in New England.  It was 3-outa-4 banner night.  We’d gotten pretty good at that kind of party. 
						 
						<p>Playing on national TV for the opening game of any NFL season was pretty cool.  Playing against a Raiders franchise I grew up rooting for was even cooler.  Having Ozzy Osbourne play “Crazy Train” LIVE right behind us as we ran out of the inflatable helmet onto the field?  Miles Davis wallpaper in an igloo can’t touch that.   
						 
						<p>Prior to the game, I spied Ozzy Osbourne and his wife Sharon strolling through the conservative halls of Gillette Stadium.  That-there folks is first-class juxtaposition. 
						 
						<p>I headed to the cafeteria to grab a bite to eat. After chow, I returned to the locker room to find a single autographed copy of Ozzy’s “Prince of Darkness” box set resting on each of the sixty-plus locker stools. 
						 
						<p>Ozzy Osbourne stuff isn’t a very high-demand item in an NFL locker room, so I walked away that day with a dozen or more of those unwanted gems.  I’ve given most of them away over the years as auction items for charity events, but I still keep one today in a desk drawer in my office. 
						 
						<p>As long as I was a Patriot, we’d always run onto the field in pregame with “Crazy Train” blaring.  I wouldn’t describe myself as an Ozzy fan necessarily.  But I dug the song for what it did; provide that lil’ pregame jolt before I ran into things. 
						 
						<p>When Ozzy himself kicked off that anthem with his famous cackle, I giggled to myself throughout the sprint onto the field.  “Crazy Train” is now a prominent song on the soundtrack of my life.  No argument here...that’s super weird. 
						 
						That evening provided the best Week 1 memory from my football career by a long shot.  And if at any point that memory starts to slip away, it’s just a tug on a desk drawer away.
					</div>
